properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions are expected beginning today through Tuesday morning. A blizzard warning is issued when winds are expected to produce blowing snow with widespread visibilities of 400 metres or less for at least 6 hours. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong low pressure system tracking toward Foxe Basin today will bring strong winds, snow and blowing snow to Naujaat. Strong northerly winds with gusts to 70 km/h along with snow and blowing snow will create a blizzard beginning overnight Monday toward Tuesday morning and last until late evening on Tuesday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An intense low pressure system is forecast to bring easterly winds of 60 gusting to 80 km/h beginning overnight Monday and continuing Tuesday. These winds will combine with falling snow to give blizzard conditions. Conditions will improve Tuesday evening as the winds diminish. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential for heavy snow this afternoon and evening. A powerful storm system is approaching from the Gulf of Alaska. Strong southerly winds in advance of this system will begin to push precipitation over the St. Elias mountains and through the Chilkat Pass late this morning. We are expecting wet snow mixed with rain. However, heavy precipitation could keep valley temperatures near the freezing mark, allowing snow to accumulate. At this time a great deal of uncertainty remains in how much warm air will invade the Shakwak Valley and how heavily it will precipitate. If a colder regime presents itself, snowfall accumulations in excess of 10 cm are possible. Snow levels are likely to fluctuate between 600 and 800 metres, which could result in relatively modest snowfall accumulations at Haines Junction and much higher amounts just outside of town along the Alaska Highway, and along the Haines Road which is under a WInter Storm Warning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

Area: Haines Junction

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A deep low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will approach the region today. As a result, heavy snow and strong winds will develop over the Haines Road and South Klondike Highway this morning. The storm will rage through the day and into the night. The snow and winds will eventually abate early Tuesday morning. ### Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.
